      {
        "id": 1707958,
        "name": "D@v1dZ",
        "username": "Dav1dZ",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/dav1dz/{size}/991_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-07-14T04:23:50.000Z",
        "cooked": "<ul>\n<li>\n<strong>2010 Domaine Bruno Clair Chambertin-Clos de B\u00e8ze</strong> <em>- France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Nuits, Chambertin-Clos de B\u00e8ze Grand Cru (7/13/2015)</em><br>\nOh my gosh.  Shockingly open, though clearly it\u2019s truly meant to age.  Explosive, room-filing nose of crushed raspberry, tart cherry, vanilla bean, roses and a touch of Chinese spice. But the palate is as savory as the nose is pretty - salty / fish sauce cutting crushed raspberry. Intense, long and concentrated.  But at the same time, mouthwatering acidity and the classic gevrey licking-a-magnet minerality show through the fruit.  There\u2019s a ton of tannin here but it\u2019s impossibly ripe and powdery.  As good a young burg as I\u2019ve ever had. Mind blowing. <em><strong>(95 pts.)</strong></em>\n</li>\n<li>\n<strong>1989 Henri Bonneau Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape R\u00e9serve des C\u00e9lestins</strong> <em>- France, Rh\u00f4ne, Southern Rh\u00f4ne, Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape (7/13/2015)</em><br>\nBy the time I had a chance to taste this it had been open a few hours, and, as I was told, was showing well worse than its spectacular peak.  Very figgy; Christmas spice, touch of soy, but good acid - this is a touch spirity but never cloying - with broad shouldered tannin and a dollop of truffle.  Lovely wine, but I\u2019m told it was spectacular an hour earlier. <em><strong>(91 pts.)</strong></em>\n</li>\n</ul>",
