      {
        "id": 1708040,
        "name": "D@v1dZ",
        "username": "Dav1dZ",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/dav1dz/{size}/991_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-07-14T12:14:22.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Gerhard P.\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Gerhard P.:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"DavidZ\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/a88e57/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> DavidZ:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>[*]<strong>1989 Henri Bonneau Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape R\u00e9serve des C\u00e9lestins</strong> <em>- France, Rh\u00f4ne, Southern Rh\u00f4ne, Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape (7/13/2015)</em><br>\nBy the time I had a chance to taste this it had been open a few hours, and, as I was told, was showing well worse than its spectacular peak.  Very figgy; Christmas spice, touch of soy, but good acid - this is a touch spirity but never cloying - with broad shouldered tannin and a dollop of truffle.  Lovely wine, but I\u2019m told it was spectacular an hour earlier. <em><strong>(91 pts.)</strong></em>[/list]</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>This is a hell of a wine, maybe even better than the 1990 C.<br>\nAlthough I\u00b4ve tasted it last a few years ago I don\u00b4t think it usually will go downhill so fast when properly opened and slow-oxed \u2026 (my positive experience with such wines \u2026) - could eventually be a result of immediate decanting \u2026  <img src=\"/uploads/db3686/original/2X/4/42a16863a8714da3c1604419e3eb9206bb87aa50.gif\" width=\"19\" height=\"27\" alt=\"[scratch.gif]\" title=\"scratch\" class=\"animated\"> (\u2026 but actually I don\u00b4t know \u2026)</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The Bonneau was double decanted about an hour before the meal.  I showed up when folks were sipping coffee, so it was decanted about 3-4 hours before I had a chance to try.  I was told it had put on much weight during the meal and had actually peaked during the main course, then began to lose some of its freshness / aromatics.  The palate was still rich and layered and showed off the wine\u2019s class.</p>",
