      {
        "id": 1708141,
        "name": "Dan Rosenheck",
        "username": "Dan_Rosenheck",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/dan_rosenheck/{size}/1395_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-07-14T15:27:04.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>So here\u2019s what it <strong>really</strong> tasted like.  Easily my leading candidate for WOTY.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=33317&amp;iNote=5106743\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>1989 Henri Bonneau Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape R\u00e9serve des C\u00e9lestins</strong></a> <em>- France, Rh\u00f4ne, Southern Rh\u00f4ne, Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape (7/14/2015)</em><br>\nZOMFG.  Kaleidoscopic, super-intense, constantly evolving nose featuring black cherry and plum, fig, candied liqueur, Christmas fruitcake, pepper, and olive.  Given the power of the nose, you\u2019d expect a wallop in the mouth, but it\u2019s deceptively finessed and elegant, on the light side of middleweight, almost muted on the attack, before depositing sequential and individually distinguishable layers of flavor on the mid- and back palate and lingering for a seemingly interminable finish and aftertaste. With air the acid shows up a bit to give some tension to the sweetness and providing even better balance.  A glorious 60-90 minute peak (from about 2-2.5 to 3.5 hours of aeration), before excessive exposure to air started to turn it burly and a bit hot. <em><strong>(95 pts.)</strong></em>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span alt=\"\" role=\"presentation\" class=\"broken-image\" title=\"This image is broken\"><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-unlink svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use href=\"#unlink\"></use></svg></span></p>\n<p><em>Posted from <a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">CellarTracker</a></em><br>\n<br>\n<br>\n\u2026and a somewhat more cautious take on the Beze:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=1299014&amp;iNote=5106745\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2010 Domaine Bruno Clair Chambertin-Clos de B\u00e8ze</strong></a> <em>- France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Nuits, Chambertin-Clos de B\u00e8ze Grand Cru (7/14/2015)</em><br>\nVery ripe, potent, focused nose of black raspberry and bubble gum.  Almost a little syrupy/Robitussin smelling.  In the mouth it\u2019s full-bodied, extremely dense, with a chewy texture, and enough acid to give it an almost piercing quality on the palate and leave a lengthy sour aftertaste.  This is one of the most concentrated and structured Burgundies I\u2019ve ever tried.  Impressively, it\u2019s enjoyable now\u2013a Bordeaux with this kind of aging capacity would be undrinkable at this stage\u2013but there\u2019s so much stuffing that I still wouldn\u2019t want to touch it for another 20 years, to see what all of these potent ingredients can add up to.  91 for current drinking, limitless potential.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span alt=\"\" role=\"presentation\" class=\"broken-image\" title=\"This image is broken\"><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-unlink svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use href=\"#unlink\"></use></svg></span></p>\n<p><em>Posted from <a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">CellarTracker</a></em></p>",
